<h2>Event in July 2018</h2>
<h3>Heat wave and drought in central and northern Europe</h3>
The blocked weather pattern over Europe that was described in the <a href="https://surfobs.climate.copernicus.eu//stateoftheclimate/june2018.php">report of June 2018</a> continued in July. High pressure systems were mainly located above northwestern Europe with exceptionally high pressure anomalies in Scandinavia and northern Russia (Figure 1).
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jul2018/rcc_eude_eur_ppp_8110_2018_07.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/rcc_eude_eur_ppp_8110_2018_07.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: July 2018 pressure anomalies (source: RCC-CM)</em>
<br><br>
This resulted in a continuation of above normal temperatures over most of Europe except Portugal, parts of Spain and parts of southeastern Europe. This situation also resulted in intensification of the drought in large parts of central and northern Europe. Figure 2 shows that temperature anomalies in Scandinavia reached values of more than +6&#176;C above average. The lower anomalies in eastern Europe were due to frequent precipitation events. At some days it was warmer in an absolute sense in southern Scandinavia than for parts of Spain.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
