<a href="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TG_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc__2018-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tg_anom_2018_1981-2010_month_nc__2018-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: TG: Mean Temperature in July 2018 (left) and anomaly w.r.t. 1981-2010 (right)</em>
<br><br>
The consecutive dry days in July 2018, in combination with the monthly precipitation sums over Europe, show the drought situation for central and northern Europe. Here the drought situation has lasted for several months, more or less through the growing season, which will reduce the harvest. The low water levels in the rivers and reservoirs induce a reduction in the shipping traffic along the rivers. The fish population in the rivers is also affected by higher water temperatures, the reduced fresh water and oxygen content. This long lasting drought together with the withered vegetation stimulated a lot of wildfires in Scandinavia, United Kingdom and Ireland. Sweden has called for emergency assistance from the European Union countries to help fight against the flames in this wide range territory. Dry summers with high numbers of consecutive dry days are usual in the popular tourist destinations in southern Europe, but not in central and northern Europe.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2018_month_nc__2018-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2018_month_nc__2018-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 3: CDD: Consecutive dry days in July 2018</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for July 2018</h2>
Extremes of minimum and maximum temperatures (Figure 4) show two aspects of the heatwave in July 2018. The index describing the warm nights is the number of days above the 90th percentile of the daily minimum temperature (TN90p, Figure 4, left). The threshold of this index is defined by sorting all daily minimum temperature values for July of the reference period 1981-2010 and taking the value at 90%. This threshold is different for every location. The percentiles of the maximum temperatures, called warm day-times, (TX90p, Figure 4, right) are defined analogously. In France, Poland, the Baltic States, Scandinavia and northeastern Europe more than the expected 3 days with warm nights occured; sometimes even more than 10 warm nights were observed. Only in Ireland, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Germany few warm nights occurred. Most of Scandinavia, United Kingdom and central Europe suffered from extreme high maximum temperatures. In Norway it was the warmest July (together with the year 2014) since 1900 when weather analyses began. Regionally, temperature deviations from the long term mean (1961-1990) were more than +6&#176;C. In most parts of Sweden, July 2018 became the warmest one noted so far. Large parts of the month were characterized by severe drought and severe forest fires. Scandinavia reported several new records for maximum temperatures. The heat wave in Scandinavia lasts in many parts for more than 10 days, longer than in any other part of Europe (Figure 5)
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tn90p_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TN90p_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jul2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_tn90p_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_TN90p_baselayers_overlay_2018-07-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
