<h2>The weather in July 2018</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
The European temperature departure with an average of +2.33&#176;C was the second highest July temperature since continental records began, trailing behind 2010 by only 0.01&#176;C. July 2018 marks the third time in the record that the European July temperature departure was on average 2.0&#176;C or higher. Norway set a new national maximum temperature record when temperatures soared to 33.5&#176;C on 17 July in Badufoss. In Sweden, the station located in Kvikkjokk observed its highest July maximum temperature at 32.5&#176;C. The previous record for this location was 32.0&#176;C set on 17 July 1945. In central and western Europe many station records for the highest maximum temperature were achieved. On July 27 parts of Germany and the Netherlands got maxima over 38&#176;C. Also remarkable were the "tropical" nights in Germany, the Low Countries and the southeastern parts of England, with minimum temperatures between 21 and 24&#176;C.
<br><br>
